    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "db84023d0c15415d",
      "text": "**3.** contribute towards the development of a transdisciplinary language (theuse of a ‘common language’) (von Bertalanffy, 1968; Kramer & de Smit,1977; Davidson, 1983; Ing, 2011) and methodology that has the potentialto share meaning across disciplines and world views, with the purpose toenable dialogue to identify and solve problems and develop humanity collectively, critically and ethically (Churchman, 1968; Beer, 1975; Cavaleri & Obloj, 1993; Ulrich, 1996; Midgley, 2000; Nicolescu, 2010)."
